    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-02-02T02:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-02-02T02:00:00-05:00" n="708"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d708">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">845C.79693/1: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Peck</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-02-02T14:00:00+07:00"
                            >February 2, 1939—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 8:37 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>69. 1. Embassy is informed that British authorities have granted China National
                    Aviation Corporation exclusive right to establish service between China
                    (Kunming) and Rangoon. Representative of China National Aviation Corporation is
                    leaving Chungking for Kunming today to meet a representative of Imperial Airways
                    to arrange details and plan an exploratory flight to Rangoon which is expected
                    after a few days.</p>
                <p>2. French authorities have granted permission to China National Aviation
                    Corporation to establish direct service between Chungking and Hanoi, French
                    Indo-China. Service expected to start as soon as details are arranged with Air
                    France. (At present Eurasia maintains Chungking–Hanoi service via Kunming.)</p>
                <p>3. Embassy is confidentially informed that Chinese Government may ask China
                    National Aviation Corporation to establish service between Szechuan and Hami,
                    Sinkiang. Company is at present short of equipment but has ordered two Douglas
                    DC–3’s and hopes for early delivery.</p>
                <p>4. Repeated to Peiping, Hong Kong, Shanghai, Kunming, Rangoon, Saigon.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Peck</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
